<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-axioms"
    xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Definition of Vector Spaces</title>
    <introduction xml:id="sm-introduction-vector-spaces-definition">
            <p>
                A vector space provides an abstract generalization of the vectors in
                <m>\R^n</m> defined before.
                In <m>\R^n</m>,
                vectors can be added and multiplied by real numbers.
                Abstract vectors will have similar operations,
                and scalars can be drawn from any field <m>\F</m>,
                not exclusively <m>\R</m>.
            </p>
            <note>
                <title>Fields</title>
                <p>
                    Fields have their own set of axioms,
                    but for our purposes we will use pre-defined fields in Sage.
                    So you may think of them as a class in Sage.
                </p>
            </note>
            <p>
                A vector space over a field of scalars
                <m>\F</m> as a nonempty set <m>V</m> of vectors,
                together with the operations, <m>+</m> vector addition
                and <m>\cdot</m> scalar multiplication,
                such that the following axioms are satisfied for all
                <m>u,v,w \in V</m> and <m>a,b \in \F</m>:
            </p>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Closure</title>
                <p>
                    <m>v + u \in V</m> and 
                    <m>a \cdot v \in V</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Commutativity</title>
                    <m>v + u = u + v</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Associativity</title>
                <p>
                    <m>(v + u) + w = v + (u + w)</m> and 
                    <m>(ab) \cdot v = a \cdot (b \cdot v)</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Additive Identity</title>
                <p>
                    There is a vector <m>\mathbf 0 \in V</m>
                    such that <m>\mathbf 0 + v = v</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Additive Inverse</title>
                <p>
                    There exists a vector, <m> -v \in V</m>
                    such that <m>v + (-v) = \mathbf 0</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Multiplicative Identity</title>
                <p>
                    <m>1 \cdot v = v</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Distributivity</title>
                <p>
                    <m>a \cdot (u + v) = a \cdot v + a \cdot u</m> and 
                    <m>(a + b) \cdot v = a \cdot v + b \cdot v</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p>
            As an example,
            <m>\R^n</m> is a vector space over <m>\R</m>
            and the set <m>\F^n</m> of <m>n</m>-tuples <m>(a_1, \ldots, a_n)</m>
            where <m>a_i \in \F</m>
            forms a vector space over <m>\F</m>.
            We will say that the dimension of these vector spaces is <m>n</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Sage allows for us to create a vector space using the <c>VectorSpace</c> command.
            We need to pass the field as well as the dimension of the space as arguments.
            For instance, the following method creates the vector space <m>\R^3</m>:
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                V = VectorSpace(RR, 3)
                V
            </input>
        </sage>
        <p>
            Let's create now the vector space <m>\Q^2</m>
            of pairs of rational numbers:
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                W = VectorSpace(QQ, 2)
                W
            </input>
        </sage>
        <p>
            Equivalently, we can define the same vector space as:
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                W = QQ ^ 2
                W
            </input>
        </sage>
        <p>
            We can check if a vector belongs to a vector space.
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                w = vector(QQ, [1,3,4])
                # Ensure that the vector is over the same field
                w in W
            </input>
        </sage>
        <!--
        <p>
        Interestingly, polynomials with real coefficients also satisfy the definition of a vector space.
        We can construct the vector space containing polynomials, with a variable <m>x</m>, of maximum degree 3 as follows:
        </p>
        <sage>
        <input>
        P_3 = VectorSpace(RR, PolynomialRing(RR, var('x'), 4))
        P_3
        </input>
        </sage>
        <note>
        <title>Free Modules</title>
        <p>
        The return type of <c>VectorSpace</c> is a <c>FreeModule</c>
        as opposed to a vector space class.
        This is a more general term and in this context can be interpreted as a vector space.
        </p>
        </note>
        <p>
        It is required by Sage to specify the variable of the polynomial when we are working with polynomials.
        </p>
        -->
    </introduction>
</section>
